    {
      "id": "intro",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "The simple past",
      "body": "# The preterite (pretérito indefinido)\n\nThe **preterite** is the simple past for **completed actions**: something that happened yesterday, last night, or at a clear point in the past and is now finished.\n\nTypical time markers (signal words):\n\n- **ayer** - yesterday\n- **anoche** - last night\n\nPresent versus past:\n\n- *Hoy **hablo** con María.* - Today I speak with María. (present)\n- *Ayer **hablé** con María.* - Yesterday I spoke with María. (past)\n\nNotice the **accent** already here: *hablo* (I speak) versus *hablé* (I spoke)."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-endings",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "The -AR endings",
      "body": "## The preterite endings (-AR)\n\nFor regular **-AR** verbs, take the stem and add these endings:\n\n| Person | Ending | Example (hablar) |\n|---|---|---|\n| yo | **-é** | habl**é** |\n| tú | **-aste** | habl**aste** |\n| él / ella | **-ó** | habl**ó** |\n| nosotros | **-amos** | habl**amos** |\n| vosotros | **-asteis** | habl**asteis** |\n| ellos / ellas | **-aron** | habl**aron** |\n\nThe **yo** form (habl**é**) and the **él/ella** form (habl**ó**) carry a **mandatory accent**. This accent is not optional - it decides the meaning. More on that on the next page.\n\nThe same pattern works for *comprar* (compré, compraste, compró, ...), *trabajar*, *estudiar*, *cocinar*."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-accent-rule",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "The accent changes the meaning",
      "body": "## The accent is mandatory - it changes the tense\n\nWithout the accent the form is **present**; with the accent it is **past**. This is the most important rule of this lesson:\n\n| Without accent (present) | With accent (past) |\n|---|---|\n| *hablo* = I speak | *habl**é*** = I spoke |\n| *habla* = he/she speaks | *habl**ó*** = he/she spoke |\n| *compro* = I buy | *compr**é*** = I bought |\n| *compra* = he/she buys | *compr**ó*** = he/she bought |\n\nA forgotten accent rewrites the tense completely.\n\n**Important exception - the nosotros form:** *hablamos* and *compramos* are **identical** in present AND past. There is no accent difference here - only the context (e.g. *ayer*) tells you whether present or past is meant."
    },
